Observation Details: While Ashlin and I were collecting 1.5 gallons of the most delicious blackberries that I have every eaten, I heard a high pitched chip reminiscent of an INBU.  Hoping for a LABU I  looked around, only to find this female CAQU sitting up in full view.  This was my first view of one since arriving.  Ashlin and I both had great looks.  I assume she was "on point" and tending a flock of hatchlings that were undetected below.   On a whim, I tried photographing her through my 10x42 Swarovskis using my iPhone.  And it worked!!  Apparently it is called "digibinning" to differentiate it from digiscoping.  To get this final image, I cropped the original photo, reduced the lightness, upped the clarity and the color.

The official state bird of California, this is a male. The oddly shaped topknot looks like a single feather, but is actually six overlapping feathers. Although locally common, this iconic species has disappeared from many urban areas such as Golden Gate Park in San Francisco where their decline is directly correlated to the introduction of feral house cats into the park. This is the darker race "C. c. brunnescens" confined to the coastal fog belt of the central California coast.

Peshastin, WA, Blewett Pass, Valleyhi Eadie backyard bird feeder
Observation Details: The nutchatches and chickadees throw seeds/nuts that they don't like from the tube feeder onto the ground.  The quail have become used to this and during the summer, often feed under the bird feeder pole.  They also feed under the suet cage because the flickers drop some pieces of suet when they eat.  I call them my "clean up crew".  We have about 2 feet of snow on the ground.  The weather has warmed up to 35-45 degrees during the day and we've seen the quail 5 times in the last 3 weeks so we've starting putting some chicken scratch feed out for them.  This morning, 33 of them came in  (and came back twice later in the day - my husband said they were resting on the ground under our trailer in the carport, which is about 15 feet from the feeder).   There are 2 big fir trees nearby that have very large witch's brooms in them - they will glide in from there and they will flush right back to the witch's broom.  When they are spooked by the Steller's Jays swooping in, they often run to the base of the large bush I have next to the feeder (being winter, it doesn't provide much cover right now).  When they come to the feeder, some glide most of the way in, and others glide part of the way, land, then run over to the feeder from 40-50 feet away.  We have several Douglas Squirrels and chipmunks that also eat under the feeder and sometimes they eat next to or in the middle of the quail group.  The quail don't seem to mind until they have babies.

However, they were near a house that had at least one domestic bird on the property, so I assumed they kept quail, too, since it sounded like the quail were right on the trail by the house. Well... the quail *were* right on the trail by the house, as they were indeed wild, and I accidentally flushed two of them. One paused on a branch a few feet in front of me and continued to sing for a minute or two (pictured).

Observation Details: Approximate number. First I saw one run across the road, then a second. Then I saw a male and a female in the grasses on the side of the road (presumably the same that crossed the road). Then they disappeared for a while, reappeared in the driveway of the property I had been staking out. Suddenly a whole bunch popped out of the grass - at first 11 quail flushed and flew into the grasses on the other side of the driveway. Then 14 more. After all were gone I still heard at least one singing "Lake Tahoe" in the grasses where they had just come from.

The official state bird of California, this is a male. The oddly shaped topknot looks like a single feather, but is actually six overlapping feathers. Although locally common, this iconic species has disappeared from many urban areas such as Golden Gate Park in San Francisco where their decline is directly correlated to the introduction of feral house cats into the park. This is the darker race "C. c. brunnescens" confined to the coastal fog belt of the central California coast.

Observation Details: The nutchatches and chickadees throw seeds/nuts that they don't like from the tube feeder onto the ground.  The quail have become used to this and during the summer, often feed under the bird feeder pole.  They also feed under the suet cage because the flickers drop some pieces of suet when they eat.  I call them my "clean up crew".  We have about 2 feet of snow on the ground.  The weather has warmed up to 35-45 degrees during the day and we've seen the quail 5 times in the last 3 weeks so we've starting putting some chicken scratch feed out for them.  This morning, 33 of them came in  (and came back twice later in the day - my husband said they were resting on the ground under our trailer in the carport, which is about 15 feet from the feeder).   There are 2 big fir trees nearby that have very large witch's brooms in them - they will glide in from there and they will flush right back to the witch's broom.  When they are spooked by the Steller's Jays swooping in, they often run to the base of the large bush I have next to the feeder (being winter, it doesn't provide much cover right now).  When they come to the feeder, some glide most of the way in, and others glide part of the way, land, then run over to the feeder from 40-50 feet away.  We have several Douglas Squirrels and chipmunks that also eat under the feeder and sometimes they eat next to or in the middle of the quail group.  The quail don't seem to mind until they have babies.
